               <p>WILLIAM THOMPSON. I live in <placeName id="t18320906-368-crimeloc2084">Hartshorn-court, Golden-lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-368-crimeloc2084" type="placeName" value="Hartshorn-court, Golden-lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-368-crimeloc2084" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-368-off2082 t18320906-368-crimeloc2084"></join>; the prisoner lodged in the same room with me. I missed these things from different drawers, on the 31st of July - I had not seen them after that; I saw the prisoner in about six hours, and told him I suspected him; he said he had pawned them, and told me where, but I have not found the clothes - the things altogether were worth 5l.; I never authorized him to pawn them.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Did you never authorize him to pledge any thing? A. Never; I never agreed not to prosecute if he would pay me 6s. a week - I am porter to Messrs. Hale and Co., oilmen.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-368-person3031">
                  HENRY 
                  PRINCE
               <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3031" type="surname" value="PRINCE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3031" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3031" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am foreman to Mr. Galloway at times. On the 31st of July, about two o'clock in the afternoon, the prosecutor, having missed his things, told me to search for the prisoner, and about half-past four o'clock, I saw him in the room, and asked what he had done with Bill's things - he cried, and said he had taken and pawned them at the corner of Worship-street; I went there next day, but the pawnbroker had left; the prisoner gave me the duplicate, which I gave the Policeman.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. You asked where he pawned them? A. Yes; he said the house was shut up, but the goods were to be delivered in Newgate-street; but there was a board on the house referring to Mr. Joyce of the New-road; I have known the prisoner fourteen years; I never said the prosecutor had agreed to take 6s. a week not to prosecute.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-368-person3032">
                  SAMUEL 
                  KNAPP
               <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3032" type="surname" value="KNAPP"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3032" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3032" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . My father is a pawnbroker in Golden-lane. I have a shaving-box and rule, pawned on the 31st of July, for 8d., in the name of 
               <persName id="t18320906-368-person3033">
                  Thomas 
                  Smith
               <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3033" type="surname" value="Smith"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3033" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3033" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             - I cannot say who by.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-368-person3034">
                  RICHARD 
                  COTTER
               <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3034" type="surname" value="COTTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3034" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3034" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. I took the prisoner; he cried, and said he had given the duplicates to Prince, who gave them to me; one of them has the name of Pickford on it.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>The prisoner delivered in a petition, expressing his contrition.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-368-person3035">
                  EDWARD 
                  HANDS
               <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3035" type="surname" value="HANDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3035" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-368-person3035" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer of St. Luke's. Prince told me the prosecutor had agreed that the prisoner should pay down 9s., and 5s. a week, and he would not prosecute him; this was about four o'clock in the afternoon - the prisoner was taken that night.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 19.</p>
